* This poem tells the story of a walk to McDonald's.

Steel wagons sharply weave
through razor beams of light,
as shattered half-conversations
punctuate the night.

With hunger in our stomachs,
in our hearts, and in our eyes,
we traipse with haste and valor
under crimson-pewter guise.

To arches great and grand,
beneath which lies our treasure,
the rich reward of Yukon,
of value beyond meausure.

And as we walk, and talk, and dance,
the docket ditches false pretense;
we share a gentle kiss or two,
our hearts a-glow with bright suspense.

At last, we stumble through my door,
and shed our feathers to the floor,
then celebrate with sacred dance,
a night of satin blythe romance.

With bellies full and spirits high,
we turn our chins up towards the sky;
And here we lie, and here we moor,
upon a warm and sandy shore.